The flight logbook is officially in use now. I have 2.3 hours of flight time recorded ^_^
#TeaganAir
If you asked me to describe what it's like to fly a small plane, I would say it's like driving a combination of a motorcycle/ATV and a boat at 4000 feet high.
On the ground, conditions change rapidly. There is a certain level of instability on the ground, so a motorcycle/ATV is needed.
By the way, you might not know that when driving an airplane on the ground, you use your feet to control the direction, not the steering stick. You use the rudder pedals and brakes. It's not a car.
When flying in the air, you feel bumps and shakes, similar to riding a boat on water. Although you can control the plane, sometimes the air currents can make you a bit disoriented, so you need to adapt to flying in the air, just as sailors adapt to sailing.
There's also a random fun fact about this:
Flying is physically demanding. My back and legs are really sore today, feeling like I just went to the gym.
This is nothing like taking a drive on Sunday. To me, a novice, it's more like a sport than a cruise.
Dear friends, happy Saturday. Welcome to 4,000 feet up high.
I will fly again tomorrow, and we will practice stalls and slow flight.
Today's weather was a bit unstable, but super fun. We practiced slow flight and stalls. Our ground speed once dropped to 16 miles per hour, while the airspeed was still at 65 miles per hour.
Today was sunny, and although there was a bit of haze up high, the view was still great.
